The paper deals with motion estimation for rail vehicles using visual and visual-inertial odometry frameworks. This falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO) as it involves the use of sensors and algorithms to estimate the motion of a vehicle. The use of visual data also suggests that computer vision (cs.CV) is a likely sub-category. The evaluation of the methods against ground truth data suggests that machine learning (cs.LG) could also be a relevant sub-category. The application of the methods to rail networks suggests that control systems (cs.SY) could also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the investigation of the challenges and limitations of the methods suggests that artificial intelligence (cs.AI) could also be a relevant sub-category.
